<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%>
	   <a name=99300874672179></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99300874672179><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=item.html?item=6210&mid=99300874672179>RE: DRuids</a> <a id=fs8 href=item.html?item=6210&mid=99300874672179#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Jun 19th 11:45 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Unfortunately at your level, you aren't yet aware of the sharp distinction in roles between the classes when this weapon would come into play.&nbsp;&nbsp;At level 20, druids and clerics can still tank and nobody new to the game thinks twice about it.  But when your group is depending on you to fulfill certain roles, e.g backup healing and evacs, and you're tanking when you're oom, then I'm sorry to say that you will not ever be welcome in a group again.  At the high-level game, it's no more about goofing off and experimenting.  To keep your group alive, you need to do what's expected of you.  In the case of the druid, it's to maintain group buffs/regen, ensuring the mobs are snared, healing when the cleric is in the middle of a CH (complete heal), and saving enough mana to evac the group when necessary.  Even when soloing, the damage done in medding up a nuke or dot is going to FAR exceed any damage you do tanking in the same time-frame.  Suffice to say, the only time you'll ever see a druid equipped with this (aside from being twinked), is when he/she is trying to impress the newbies in the orc camps.  (And even then, a nice Scoriae is far more impressive.)<br><br>Ruark,<br>52 Wanderer<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
